This paper deals with a communication system using non-orthogonal multiple access (NOMA) and joint decoding techniques, which are commonly studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The paper also considers the impact of system conditions such as load, received powers, and interference, which are relevant to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of Rayleigh fading and path loss channel models suggests a focus on multimedia (cs.MM) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories, which often deal with signal processing and statistical modeling.
